\fs51\fsmilli25995 5 | Nutrition and Metabolism
\fs21\fsmilli10995 In this lesson, students learn how the body uses food to get energy and build new materials. We\
explain that food contains nutrients (carbohydrates, proteins, fats, vitamins, and minerals) which\
the digestive system breaks down into usable parts. For example, carbohydrates are turned into\
glucose (blood sugar) for energy, proteins into amino acids for muscle and cell repair, and fats\
into fatty acids for long-term energy and cell membranes. We introduce metabolism as all the\
chemical reactions in the body that transform nutrients into energy and building blocks. We also\
mention that vitamins and minerals (like iron, calcium, and vitamins C and D) help cells work\
properly.\
After this lesson, students will understand that eating balanced meals gives the body fuel\
(energy) and materials to grow. They will know the main roles of carbohydrates (energy),\
proteins (growth/repair), and fats (energy storage and insulation). They will also learn that\
excessive sugar or fat can cause health issues, while vitamins and minerals are important in\
small amounts.
