\fs51\fsmilli25995 6 | Kidneys and Body Balance
\fs21\fsmilli10995 In this lesson, students study the kidneys and the urinary system. We explain that the kidneys\
act like filters for the blood: they remove waste and extra water to form urine (pee). Each\
minute, the kidneys filter about half a cup of blood. We describe how urine (containing water,\
salt, and waste chemicals) leaves the kidneys, goes down ureters to the bladder (where it is\
stored), and then is released through the urethra when you urinate. For example, if you drink a\
lot of water, your kidneys remove the excess by making more urine. We also explain that\
kidneys help balance the body\'92s salt, water, and pH levels so cells work properly.\
After this lesson, students will know that kidneys are vital for cleansing the blood and\
maintaining a stable internal environment. They will understand that urine contains body wastes\
and that staying hydrated helps the kidneys remove toxins. They will also learn why it is\
dangerous if kidneys fail (toxic buildup) and why drinking enough water helps kidney function.
