\fs51\fsmilli25995 7 | Brain, Nerves, and the Senses
\fs21\fsmilli10995 In this lesson, students explore the nervous system, especially the brain and senses. We\
explain that the brain is the control center of the body: it receives information from sensory\
organs and sends instructions to muscles and glands. We introduce neurons (nerve cells) that\
carry electrical signals through nerves. For example, when you touch a hot surface, sensory\
nerves send a quick message to the spinal cord and brain, which then tell your hand to pull back\
(a reflex). We also cover the five senses: eyes (vision), ears (hearing), nose (smell), tongue\
(taste), and skin (touch/pain). Each sense organ detects specific stimuli (like light or sound) and\
sends signals to the brain to interpret.\
After this lesson, students will know that the brain and nerves form the nervous system,\
controlling everything we do. They will be able to name the five senses and know that the brain\
processes all sensory information. They will understand that the nervous system acts very fast,\
allowing us to react immediately (like pulling away from a hot object).
