\fs51\fsmilli25995 8 | Hormones and the Endocrine System
\fs21\fsmilli10995 In this lesson, students learn about hormones and how glands regulate the body. We explain\
that hormones are chemical messengers made by special glands (endocrine glands) that travel\
in the bloodstream to control activities. For example, the pancreas produces insulin (a hormone)\
that signals cells to take up sugar from blood; if no insulin is made, blood sugar stays high\
(diabetes). Another example is the adrenal glands releasing adrenaline (epinephrine) when you\
are scared or exercise, which raises heart rate and blood sugar for quick energy. We describe\
other glands: the thyroid (controls metabolism and growth), pituitary (master gland that signals\
others), and ovaries/testes (releasing sex hormones for puberty and reproduction).\
After this lesson, students will know that the endocrine system complements the nervous\
system to regulate the body over longer times. They will understand that hormones control\
growth, energy use, and stress responses. They will also learn that hormone imbalance can\
cause conditions (like diabetes or growth disorders) and that puberty changes are due to\
hormones.
