\fs51\fsmilli25995 11 | Vaccines and Medicines
\fs21\fsmilli10995 In this lesson, students explore how vaccines and medicines help prevent and treat diseases.\
We explain that a vaccine is a harmless form of a germ (or a piece of it) that is given by injection\
or mouth. Vaccines train the immune system by prompting it to make antibodies against a\
disease without causing illness. For example, a flu shot contains inactivated flu virus so the\
body learns to fight it. We also describe antibiotics (medicine that kill or stop bacteria) and\
contrast them with antiviral drugs. For example, penicillin (an antibiotic) can cure strep throat\
(bacterial) but not a cold (viral). We touch on pain relievers (acetaminophen, ibuprofen) that\
reduce fever and pain, and how doctors use different medicines to treat different illnesses.\
After this lesson, students will know that vaccines prevent diseases by preparing the immune\
system, and that antibiotics are used to treat bacterial infections. They will understand why we\
don\'92t give antibiotics for viral diseases and why completing a vaccine schedule is important for\
community health (herd immunity).
