\fs51\fsmilli25995 12 | Diabetes and Metabolic Disorders
\fs21\fsmilli10995 In this lesson, students learn about diabetes mellitus, a common metabolic disease. We explain\
that diabetes occurs when the body cannot control blood sugar properly. In type 1 diabetes, the\
pancreas does not make enough insulin (often diagnosed in children or teens). In type 2\
diabetes, the body\'92s cells ignore insulin (often related to obesity). We describe the effects:\
without insulin, glucose stays in the blood, causing high blood sugar (hyperglycemia).\
Symptoms include excessive thirst, frequent urination (to rid excess sugar), fatigue, and blurred\
vision. We emphasize management: monitoring blood sugar, insulin injections for type 1, and\
diet/exercise to improve sensitivity for type 2.\
After this lesson, students will understand what diabetes is and how it affects the body. They will\
know why insulin is crucial for lowering blood glucose and what symptoms indicate high blood\
sugar. They will also learn that a healthy diet and exercise help prevent or manage type 2\
diabetes.
