\fs51\fsmilli25995 14 | Cancer and Cell Growth
\fs21\fsmilli10995 In this lesson, students learn about cancer in basic terms. We explain that cancer is a disease of\
the cells: normally, cells grow and divide in a controlled way. Cancer happens when cells grow\
uncontrollably and do not die when they should. This can lead to tumors (masses of cells) that\
can spread to other parts of the body (metastasis). We may mention a few common types:\
leukemia (blood cells become cancerous), lymphoma (lymphatic cells), or solid tumors (in\
organs like breast, lung). We also discuss risk factors: some are random (DNA mistakes), and\
some are lifestyle-related (smoking, UV exposure from sun, certain viruses like HPV). For\
example, smoking can cause lung cancer because tobacco chemicals damage DNA in lung\
cells.\
After this lesson, students will know that cancer is caused by genetic mutations leading to\
uncontrolled cell growth. They will understand that cancer cells can spread, and that early\
detection (like skin checks or doctor exams) improves outcomes. They will also learn the\
general idea of treatments: surgery to remove tumors, chemotherapy (drugs that kill\
fast-growing cells), and radiation therapy (high-energy rays to target cancer cells).
