\fs21\fsmilli10995 In this lesson, students learn about common respiratory problems like asthma and allergies. We\
explain that asthma is a condition where the airways in the lungs become narrow and inflamed,\
making it hard to breathe. Triggers can include dust, pollen, exercise, or cold air. For example, a\
child with asthma might use an inhaler (with medication) when they wheeze. We also describe\
allergies: when the immune system overreacts to harmless things (allergens) like pollen, pet\
dander, or peanut protein. Allergies can cause sneezing, itching, hives (skin rash), or even\
life-threatening reactions (anaphylaxis) in severe cases. We stress how avoiding triggers and\
using medications (inhalers for asthma, antihistamines or EpiPens for allergies) can control\
these conditions.\
After this lesson, students will understand that asthma affects breathing by tightening air\
passages and that allergies are immune reactions to ordinary substances. They will know that\
these are not contagious and often start in childhood. They will learn the importance of\
recognizing triggers (like smoke or certain foods) and seeking medical help when needed.
